<br>Hello Bhaskar Chowdhury,<br>

I've got many tips to my inbox after the last email.
For today, I picked only one which you might find interesting.
It's a tip by Eivar ( https://el2.convertkit-mail.com/c/4zuqzmrokwu7uqolp4t=
x/48hvhehrr0o40/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9laXZhcg=3D=3D ).

He loves vim-plug plugin manager, because (among other features)
it has the ability to activate plugins on demand.

First, you would need to install the plugin:
https://github.com/junegunn/vim-plug (
https://el2.convertkit-mail.com/c/4zuqzmrokwu7uqolp4tx/mvu7h5h88ord2/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9naXRodWIuY29tL2p1bmVndW5uL3ZpbS1wbHVn )

Then, in your .vimrc you can load your plugins on-demand, like:

call plug#begin('~/.vim/vimplug')
Plug 'scrooloose/nerdtree', { 'on': 'NERDTreeToggle' }
Plug 'tpope/vim-fireplace', { 'for': 'clojure' }
call plug#end()
This way you can keep loaded plugins to the minimum, loading only
what you need for the actual project of yours.

Cheers,
Jovica

